posts.com: "Real Emo" only consists of the dc Emotional Hardcore scene and the late 90's Screamo scene. What is known by "Midwest Emo" is nothing but Alternative Rock with questionable real emo influence. When people try to argue that bands like My Chemical Romance are not real emo, while saying that Sunny Day Real Estate is, I can't help not to cringe because they are just as fake emo as My Chemical Romance (plus the pretentiousness). Real emo sounds ENERGETIC, POWERFUL and somewhat HATEFUL. Fake emo is weak, self pity and a failed attempt to direct energy and emotion into music. Some examples of REAL EMO are Pg 99, Rites of Spring, Cap n Jazz (the only real emo band from the midwest scene) and Loma Prieta. Some examples of FAKE EMO are American Football, My Chemical Romance and Mineral EMO BELONGS TO HARDCORE NOT TO INDIE, POP PUNK, ALT ROCK OR ANY OTHER MAINSTREAM GENRE

>>115002134
Coming from someone who has learned DJing and done shows and has been learning production for three years, it's not comparable at all. It's going to take a lot more time to get better at production than learning how to mix that I can't recommend learning how to DJ unless you really have a passion for it. You're way better off learning how DAWs and synthesizers work if you want to produce UKG, the DJing can wait until later.

One of the only few positives I can think of when it comes to learning how to DJ from a production standpoint is that it forces you to listen to a lot of music which helps you develop your taste on what good and bad music is, but you should already be doing that if you're a fan of music. Beyond that it's good from a marketing standpoint, but that shouldn't matter until you become a real artist. Just pick up reaper and vital and go search on youtube for a few tutorials to get you started on your journey.

>>115025024
Different anon here. Any DAW will be intimidating the first time you open it if you've never used one before. You just have to power through some beginner's tutorials until you know how to:
>navigate the software's GUI
>configure your audio/MIDI drivers and settings
>record stuff (after arming the track and selecting the right inputs)
>use virtual instruments and edit MIDI
>add effects
>arrange clips on the timeline
>export your songs

Those are the main things to start with. It helps to break it all down into manageable topics instead of seeing "music production" as some huge mountain to climb all at once. Eventually, you'll also want to learn how to
>manage/organize the way you save files
>scan for 3rd party plugins
>use automation for different parameters
>learn keyboard shortcuts
>etc.

But once you get past the first list I wrote, you can just experiment and look up individual topics as you think of them. When I first started, it helped to keep a list of topics I wanted to learn as I thought of them. It always felt good to scratch off a whole page of stuff that used to baffle me. Hang in there anon, you got this.

here's kind of a look at what i do when mastering. left one is crushed down with limiting and saturation and blended in. the right is pretty much completely open with just a bit of filtering and pulling out a couple whistling high freqs.

on the squished one i pull out below 200hz before going into any compression as well as any other freqs i wanna avoid triggering the compressor too much. then i'll either recover pulled freqs slightly later in the chain or pull them even more like 250hz. that pull on 500 was good on that mix as well, and a tiny boost at 800hz has been a great source of warmth for me lately.

posts.com: Herr Weingartner does not confine himself to speaking of the eccentricities of conductors, but has a good deal to say about the unpleasantness which the post of opera-conductor in Germany generally involves. Nor is he silent as to the tricks which, Eulenspiegel-like, he has himself played off upon the public and critics. He amusingly relates that some ten years ago he and his friend Alfred Reisenauer had agreed to play Liszt's Symphonic Poem "Die Ideale" and his "Faust" Symphony, arranged for two pianofortes, at a Concert of the Cassel Wagner Society. The committee begged that they would not introduce two compositions of the "horrible" Liszt, as this would drive the public away. They stuck to their resolution, played both works, but announced "Die Ideale" as a "Fantasia for two pianofortes, by Franz Schubert (after the 'Unfinished' Symphony, the master's last work)," which naturally did not exist. It was most warmly received by the public, and was generally spoken of by the press as a "pearl of Schubertian melody." Only one of the critics discovered in it an element which was strange to and far-fetched for the lyrical Schubert. The "Faust" Symphony, on the other hand, was roundly abused.

>>115008128
It's a zeuhl chart. Zeuhl is a subgenre of prog that is characterized by operatic, booming vocals often in made up languages, aggressive, chaotic and frantic sounding composition similar to brutal prog and free jazz. Personally, I love zeuhl and you should take a listen to a bunch of these albums. If you decide to take a listen, you gotta listen to MAGMA (at least Mekanik Destruktiw Kommandoh), Koenji Hyakkei, Ruins, ZAO, Corima, eX-Girl, Amygdala and Eskaton. Have fun.

>>115032457
>Both Coltrane and Vander sound like shamans channeling something otherworldly through their music
You should listen to Leon Thomas. He does the vocals on Pharoah Sander's Karma, and his voice as this weird vibrating/undulating texture that's similar to Coltrane's sax playing. It really sounds like the kind of otherworldly shamanic vibe you describe, but with some funky rhythms.
But yeah, I love how Vander took Coltrane's celestial vibe and recontextualzied it in prog. There are a fuckton of people playing different instruments and genres that were inspired by Trane, but Magma is easily one of the best ones. If you want to know more about how Magma takes elements from Coltrane, you should watch this interview. It also acts as a neat summary of the best Coltrane albums.
www.youtube.com/watch?v=72XDFItoJ00

I went my entire time in high school never trying it and hearing potheads constantly talk about how great it is. In the military it was the same exact thing. I get out of the military, finally try weed, and immediately realize it's a garbage-tier drug for me despite all of the hype. All it did was make me feel retarded, slow, and slumped. Listening to music was no better on weed (except for 1 single time when I was baked out of my mind and my buddy put Gold Soul Theory on. Never been able to recreate that sensation again).

If you want to actually enhance your music experience, LSD is the way to go. The music will take you places you'd never been. You will travel to other dimensions and meet deities or whatever. It's pretty cool. Even weed music is better on LSD. I could listen to Planet Caravan on LSD on repeat and have an entirely different experience each and every single time.

Sorry you feel that way, but he was heavily influenced by his then-girlfriend (a few years in early 60s) Suze Rotolo, who's parents were famous communists and who was self-described as a "red diaper baby." Dylan was a Midwest kid who was highly impressionable when he moved to NYC, all the new ideas about unity, revolution and equality must have been intoxicating (along with all the literal intoxicants he was ingesting by the truckload)

There are interesting write-ups about these years, I'll try to find something. But at a glimpse it appears the communists and their movement were using young Dylan to push their messages to youth. To his credit it seems he realized they were trying to use him as a sort of figurehead for their agenda and he forcefully backed out of the "movement," but not before writing his biggest folk songs with a massive communist bent to them

After that he got lost in a stupor of psychedelics, opiates and speed which seemed to propel his writing into more surrealist absurdism, some beautiful stuff to be certain, but it's hard to know if they guy ever really had a core, if there actually was a solid form of a human beneath all the violent changes in artistic and personal direction

>>115043115
>how shallow and artificial as fuck it is
How? What's artificial? Or shallow? I find XTC to have sme of the greatest songwriting chops in pop music, if not the best. The arrangements are always God tier, the melodies are catchy as fuck, yet the overall harmonic structure is always fascinating. The interplay between Andy and Dave Gregory feels like a breath a fresh air in guitar based music since they avoid any rock and roll clichees and come up with something truly engaging and inspiring.
All of their albums keep on giving, I can hardly think of another pop band whose albums have such relistening qualities.
I guess their Englishness is a bit off putting for certain people, but that's really the key: you have to relate to them and let yourself immersed with their universe. Only in that moment you'll hear what's so great and long lasting about XTC.

>>115019027
Listened to the first four songs. This is an interesting evolution of your style, it merges the instrumentation and melodies of american Country music with the overblown, noisy Rock that you typically made in a very natural way. The ideas in every song don't feel repetitive or derivative of one another, the joyful Country piano and guitar riffs paired with the Noise Rock freakouts of The Charm of The Countryside works perfectly as an opener, Texas Candles reflects a more laidback sound with his tempo and slide guitar solos and A Small Man Named Wyoming follows the previous ideas named. A Sound Mirage is perhaps a song that doesn't fit a lot with the theme of the album. Recommended.
>>115019075
I love your new song. I like how the chromatisms give a sense of mistery on the piano melodies and how the bassline and the cymbal patterns just builds that feeling even more. If I had to nitpick something that would be the fact that the sections close to the end of the song sound like more variations of the idea presented before instead of something new that creates a higher contrast, but to be honest that would damage the easy going progression that the track has. Recommended and looking forward for your new album :DDDD

shows are awesome man. yeah i imagine that’s how it goes getting tix in a big big city like Portland. altho what can I say, I managed to scoop tix to see 2 big ish bands in big ish cities. but i was on top of my game and literally autistically stayed up for those tix and bought them the literally second the presale started. sometimes it be like that.

as for the actual show experience ive gone to concerts with family, friends, many times sober and inebriated so
to that end i find its best enjoyed with either a friend that is equally hyped for the music, or alone, while a little cross faded, and maybe tripping on a light dose of LSD. 100-200microgram kinda trip.

would not recommend if you so anti social you can’t look people in the eyes or talk, unless you can actually just tune all that out and treat it as a listening experience rather than a social event.

to me it’s cool your lives are both linked together for a moment, you are getting a small piece of that persons time and a totally unqiue performance that will never be witnessed but you and the others around, sure maybe in video if you record by people on YouTube but not experienced in the way you did first hand.

I took some vids at a concert, a concert which wasn’t officially fully recorded, or released afaik and idk if other people were recording, im sure they were at some points of the show, but idk if they caught the unique moment I did. we each walked away with our own part of the concert that night, but anyway I messaged my part to the musician involved, because one of the people he was on stage with for the first time ever died, and he said it genuinely brought him to tears. not to mention i got him to sign a tape of mine at that show as well. But it’s stuff like that, which makes concerts a worthwhile thing for me, and really something I think everyone should partake in atleast once.

I’ve been rambling like fuck

This might not be the right place to request this, but since this is a Share thread, I thought I would ask for people's help.

I'm looking for a download of a compilation bootleg called The Birth of Grateful Dead. (NOT to be confused with the official release entitled Birth of The Dead)
This came out in the early 1990s on the "Unbelievable Music" label with the number UM 033.
It has early studio recordings from 1966, I believe. I don't know if they were The Grateful Dead yet, or still The Warlocks. Also on this bootleg is an outtake from AOXOMOXOA called "The Grateful Dead Meets The Mothers of Invention" (On other studio bootlegs, I've seen this piece under the title Barbed Wire Whipping Party. It's basically a recording of the band huffing nitrus oxide while a group of people in the background chant "Give me my meat") It also has Micky's "Rap" version of Fire On The Mountain, a rather nice studio version of Mason's Children, and one of the few and rare Lovelight performances where Janis Joplin joins Pig Pen.
Any help in finding a download would be appreciated.
I have a friend who think they don't like The Grateful Dead because they've met nothing but the stereotypical "Drop LSD and save the world" type of head, and thinks all Grateful Dead are Workingman's Dead and American Beauty, and I just KNOW that if they heard this bootleg, they would instantly change their mind.

Again, any help in tracking down a download would be appreciated.

Thanks in advance.

Jefferson Airplane Takes Off (Original vinyl FIRST PRESSING)
>Proto-Psychedelic rock and roll
>Haight-Asbury pre-Hippy music
>Your great grandparents dropped LSD to this when it was still legal
>NO GRACE SLICK
Originally, there was only a pressing of 500 copies of this album, as RCA Records wanted to jump on the hipie band wagon, but didn't think Jefferson Airplane would be known outside of San Francisco.

They lyrics to Let Me In are different than on later pressings, (The original version would later reappear on a Jefferson Airplane compilation in the late 1980s Jefferson Airplane Loves You) and Running Around was pulled due to it's controversial lyrics, but would later end up reissued on a compilation called Early Flight.

Pink Floyd-Animals (8-Track version)
>Psychedelic Prog Rock
>Political Music
>Musical interpretation of George Orwell's Animal Farm
For those not in the know, The 8-Track version is slightly different than what has been released on vinyl, cassette, and C.D.

The song Pigs On The Wing is one complete song instead of two separate songs. There is a guitar solo by "Snowy White" to bridge the two parts together. This was done to make the 8-Track version seamless and streamlined.
This has never been reissued either on vinyl, cassette, or C.D.

music is a secondary part of music for them the celebrity and shared experience with other normies is more important than whether or not the music is actually good which is why marketing > substance

they have but do they? it is in a very real sense their fault for being so easily lead

thinking about it now, i blame mtv
the comparatively high cost of creating a great music video, which was an important part of becoming widely popular when they were all the rage, precluded small artists from even trying without a publisher which handed all the power to them
add to this that mtv replaced a lot of radio creating an even fewer and less competitive channels of music further centralising it
popular music is very much self reinforcing and so when you have a situation in which a publisher is necessary not only to even enter the field but also to get on the airwaves you really have a recipe for disaster because most publishers are there to make money not music
that leads us to where we are now which is where publishers take the cheapest lowest common denominator punts possible since marketing is really where it's worth spending money
not that nothing slips through the cracks

I wonder how music would've been different if TV hadn't been invented. The early spirit of rock and metal seems to be heavily influenced by, abd popularized by visual spectacle, from Elvis twerking his ding dong to Jimi Hendrix burning his guitar to a Keith Moon blowing up his drums to Kiss' makeup and stage show. Dangerous, rebellious, sacrificial, antisocial. This essence must be examined and experienced. Artistic inspiration of human beings in a culture and a world is more complicated than what A.I can derive from. It can not access the chaos of embodiment including senses, emotions, passions, and mortality. Trends in metal thought that "we should be maximally tech/brutal/satanic/heavy", for example, are spiritually inferior to the flaming guitar. Computers can handle that simple logic a billion trillion times and eventually get it right. Musicians who want to be artists in the 20th century will have to prove they have souls. Music will once again have to be more than just sound.

because metal in the 80s was developing at a fast enough pace that one or two years made a WORLD of difference. The NWOBHM started in 1979, by 1980 Iron Maiden had debuted influencing literally every subsequent metal band, in 1981 you had Venom paving out the way for extreme metal, by 1982 Metallica had released their first demo tapes combining Maiden and Venom into a single thing called thrash metal, in 1984 you had Bathory releasing the first black metal album and in 1985 you had Possessed releasing the first death metal album,

For Metallica, the NWOBHM is as much of a mythological thing as Metallica themselves is to the metalcore scene
